This paper is about using deep learning for brain tumor segmentation, which is a common problem in medical image analysis. The paper specifically focuses on glioma segmentation, which is a type of brain tumor that has a structured nature with edematous tissue surrounding mutually-exclusive regions of enhancing and non-enhancing tumor. This suggests that the paper is likely to be in the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category, as it involves analyzing medical images to identify different types of tissue. Additionally, the paper uses deep neural networks, which are a common tool in machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also involves training multiple models in a tree structure, which suggests that it may be relevant to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper is likely to involve natural language processing (cs.CL) to some extent, as it involves interpreting medical images and generating segmentations.
